Why Use Gunicorn with FastAPI?
        Because:
            Gunicorn is EXCELLENT at Process Management
        Gunicorn gives:
            Multiple worker processes
            Worker lifecycle management
            Auto-restart
            Graceful shutdown
            Signal handling
            Production stability
            Load balancing between workers

        But Gunicorn itself:
            does NOT understand async ASGI directly
            was built for WSGI

        So we combine:
            Gunicorn = Process Manager
            Uvicorn = ASGI Server

    The Important Architecture

        When you run:

            gunicorn -k uvicorn.workers.UvicornWorker app:app

            You are NOT turning Gunicorn into ASGI.

            Instead:

                Gunicorn
                   └── starts multiple Uvicorn workers
                           └── each Uvicorn worker runs ASGI app

                   Architecture:

                            Gunicorn Master Process
                                     │
                    ┌────────────────┼────────────────┐
                    │                │                │
               Uvicorn Worker   Uvicorn Worker   Uvicorn Worker
                    │                │                │
                 FastAPI          FastAPI          FastAPI

        Gunicorn only:
            manages workers
            distributes traffic
            restarts crashed workers

        Uvicorn workers:
            handle ASGI
            run event loop
            execute async code
    Real-World Analogy

    Imagine a large restaurant.

        Gunicorn = Restaurant Manager

        The manager:

            hires chefs
            monitors chefs
            replaces sick chefs
            assigns tables
            manages shifts

            But the manager does NOT cook.

        Uvicorn Worker = Chef

        The chef:

            actually cooks food
            handles orders
            works asynchronously

        FastAPI = Kitchen Logic
        The recipes/business logic.

Why Not Use Only Uvicorn?

    You can:
        uvicorn app:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000

    Good for:
        development
        small deployments

    But production systems need:

        multiple CPU workers
        crash recovery
        process supervision
        graceful reloads

    Gunicorn solves this.

Deep Dive: Why Multiple Workers Matter

    Python has:

        GIL (Global Interpreter Lock)

        One process cannot fully utilize all CPU cores efficiently.

        Suppose:

            8 CPU cores
            one Uvicorn process

            Then only one core is mainly used.

            Gunicorn solves this by spawning:

                8 Uvicorn worker processes

            Now:

                each worker has its own Python process
                each has its own event loop
                multiple CPU cores are utilized
        Important Misconception

            Many people think:

                Gunicorn handles async

                Wrong.

                Actually:

                    Uvicorn handles async
                    Gunicorn handles process management
    What Happens Internally
        Step 1
            Client sends HTTP request.
            GET /users
        Step 2
            Gunicorn master receives connection.
        Step 3
            Gunicorn forwards request to one worker.
        Step 4
            Worker is actually:
                UvicornWorker
        Step 5
            Uvicorn:
                runs asyncio event loop
                executes FastAPI async endpoint

Why ASGI Needs Event Loop

    ASGI apps rely on:

        asyncio
        non-blocking sockets
        cooperative multitasking

    Uvicorn provides:
        event loop
        async HTTP protocol handling
        WebSocket handling

    Gunicorn alone cannot do this.

Worker Types in Gunicorn

    Gunicorn supports many worker types.

    Traditional WSGI:

        gunicorn app:app

    Uses:

        sync workers

    ASGI:

        gunicorn -k uvicorn.workers.UvicornWorker app:app

    Uses:

        Uvicorn ASGI workers

    The -k means:

        worker class

Production Architecture (Typical)

    Real production deployment:

        Nginx
           ↓
        Gunicorn
           ↓
        Uvicorn Workers
           ↓
        FastAPI

    Why Nginx in Front?

        Because Nginx handles:

            SSL termination
            static files
            reverse proxy
            buffering
            rate limiting

    Gunicorn/Uvicorn focus on Python app execution.

Performance Perspective
        Uvicorn Alone

            Good:

                lightweight
                fast

            Bad:

                limited process management
        Gunicorn + Uvicorn

        Best for production:
            resilient
            scalable
            multi-core support
            mature deployment model

Modern Alternative

    Nowadays many teams directly use:

        uvicorn --workers 4 app:app

    because newer Uvicorn versions support workers.

    But Gunicorn is still widely used because:

        battle-tested
        mature UNIX process management
        reliable in Linux production environments

Gunicorn itself is a WSGI process manager, but when used with uvicorn.workers.UvicornWorker, it acts as a master process that manages multiple Uvicorn ASGI worker processes.
Gunicorn handles worker management, restarts, and load balancing, while Uvicorn handles the ASGI async event loop and request processing for FastAPI applications.
