When a browser or mobile app sends a request to your python backend:
    client Request -> Web Server -> Python Application -> Response
    Python applications need a communication standard between the web server and your app.
    That standard is:
        WSGI -> old synchronous standard
        ASGI -> Modern asynchronous standard
        Uvicorn -> an ASGI server implementation

What is WSGI ?
    WSGI = Web Server Gateway Interface
    it is a standard that defines: How a Python web server communicates with a python web application.
    Introduced for traditional synchronous Python web apps

How WSGI works:
    Client -> Gunicorn/uWSGI -> FastAPI app

WSGI processes:
    one request
    one worker/thread
    one response
    then move to next request
It is blocking/synchronous

Imagine:
    Restaurant waiter = worker
    Customer request = HTTP request
In WSGI:
    Waiter takes one order
    Waits for kitchen
    Delivers food
    Then takes next order
The waiter cannot handle another customer while waiting
That is synchronous/blocking behavior

Problem with ASGI:
    suppose your app calls:
        Database
        External API
        Redis
        Kafka
        RabbitMQ
    These operations take time.
    In WSGI : Worker waits idle until operation complete
This Causes:
    Poor concurrency
    More threads/processes needed
    Higher memory usage
When to use WSGI:
    App is mostly synchronous
    Traditional CRUD application
    Low-medium traffic
    Legacy enterprise apps
Real-World WSGI Example
    Banking Admin Portal
    Imagine:
        Internal HR system
        Admin dashboard
        Employee management portal

        Requests are:
            Simple
            Low concurrency
            Mostly database CRUD

    WSGI works perfectly.

What is ASGI:
    ASGI = Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface
    It is the modern successor to WSGI
    It supports:
        Async programming
        WebSockets
        Long-lived connections
        High concurrency
How ASGI Works:
    Client -> Uvicorn/Hypercorn -> FastAPI app
        Request can pause without blocking worker
    This is the power of async/await
Example:
    Waiter takes order
    Sends to kitchen
    Moves to another customer while waiting

    One Waiter handles many customers efficiently
    That is asynchronous concurrency
ASGI Core Idea
    When app waits for:
        DB query
        External API
        File I/O
        Kafka message
        Redis operation

The server can process other requests meanwhile.
example:
    from fastapi import FastAPI
    import asyncio

    app = FastAPI()

    @app.get("/")
    async def home():
        await asyncio.sleep(5)
        return {"message": "Hello"}
    await asyncio.sleep(5)

    does NOT block the server.
    Other requests continue processing.
Why ASGI is Powerful for FastAPI
    FastAPI is designed around:
        Async I/O
        High concurrency
        Modern APIs

That is why FastAPI uses ASGI.

Real-World ASGI Example
    Food Delivery App
    Imagine:
        Thousands of users
        Real-time order tracking
        Notifications
        WebSockets
        Live driver location
    ASGI is ideal because:
        Many simultaneous users
        Many waiting operations
        Real-time communication

WebSocket Support
    WSGI cannot properly support WebSockets.
    ASGI can.
    Example:
        Chat applications
        Live stock market
        Live cricket scores
        Gaming servers
from fastapi import WebSocket

@app.websocket("/ws")
async def websocket_endpoint(ws: WebSocket):
    await ws.accept()

    while True:
        data = await ws.receive_text()
        await ws.send_text(f"Message: {data}")
