#idempotent in RestAPI
    1.An operation is idempotent if making the same request multiple times produces the same result as making it once.
        Not Same response -but same effect on server state.
    Making the same request multiple times will always produce the same result(no additional side effects after the first call)
    Repeating it 1 time or 100 times ->> same outcome on the server

    Think of a light switch:
        Turning it ON once ->> light is ON
        Turning it ON again ->> still ON(no change) This is idempotent

        Idempotent HTTP Methods:
            GET (Idempotent)
                Fetch data
                No change in server state
            Calling multiple times ->>same data

            PUT(Idempotent)
                Replace resource completely
                Sending it multiple times:
                    User remains "venkat"
                    No extra changes

            DELETE /users/123(Idempotent)
                First call → user deleted ✅
                Second call → user already gone ✅
                Final state → user does not exist
        Non - Idempotent Methods:
            POST(Not Idempotent)
                Each request creates a new user
                multiple calls ->> multiple records
            PATCH(Usually Not Idempotent)
                if it increments
    Why Idempotency Matters:
        Safe retries:
            if a request fails(network issue),you can retry without risk
        Distributed systems:
            Prevents duplicate operations in microservices.
        Prevents bugs:
            Avoids unintended duplicate data(payments,orders etc).
    Even POST can be made idempotent using:
        Idempotent keys
    same key -processed only once

