Background Task:
    A Background task is a process that runs after the API responses is sent,allowing the application to perform  time-consuming operations in the background without making the user wait.
    It helps in non-blocking execution -- meaning the main request thread is free to handle new requests while the background task continues running.

    Key points:
        Runs after the response is sent to the client(non-blocking)
        Used to perform time-consuming or secondary operations in the background.
        Keeps the API fast and responsive -- user doesn't have to wait.
        Perfect for tasks that don't need instant results.
        Frees up the main thread for handling new incoming requests.
        Helps achieve asynchronous execution without blocking other requests.
    use cases:
        sending emails or notifications
        uploading or processing large files
        Generating reports or PDFs
        Running background AI or ML model predictions
        cleaning up old data or logs
        saving analytics or tracking user activity asynchronously
    Example:
        def send_mails():
            sleep(10)
            print("Email sent")
        @app.get("/")
        async def main(bg:BackgroundTasks):
            bg.add_task(send_mails)
            return "Welcome"
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What is CORS?
    CORS = Cross-Origin Resource Sharing
    It is a security rule implemented by the browser
    CORS controls frontend->>backend communication when origins are different.
    Origin = protocol+domain+port
    Example:
        FastAPI:http://locahost:8000
        React:http://localhost:3000
    since ports differ ->> origin is different ->> CORS rule applies.
Why CORS Exists?
    CORS exists to protect user and backend APIs.
    Prevents malicious websites from calling backend APIs without permission
    Example: A fake website should not access your backend data.
    When backend doesn't allow the origin ->> browser throws error
        Blocked by CORS policy
    Important:
        Request reaches backend
        Backend sends response
        but browser blocks response due to missing CORS headers

How Browser Allows Cross-Origin?
    Browser checks if backend sends permission headers
    Backend must send:
        Access-control-Allow-Origin
    Example:
        Access-Control-Allow-Origin:http://localhost:3000
    Browser also checks:
        allowed methods:GET/POST/PUT?DELETE
        allowed headers:Authorization,Content-Type
    If allowed ->> browser shows response to frontend


CORS in Middleware:
    middleware runs before API route and after route response
    CORS must apply to all endpoints(global solution)
    Middleware automatically:
        adds CORS headers to every response
        handles OPTIONS preflight request
    Without middleware, you must manually add headers in every API
    So middleware is the standard + clean approach

 FastAPI CORS Middleware Code:
    from fastapi import FastAPI
    from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware
    app= FastAPI()
    app.add_middleware(CORSMiddleware,
                        allow_origins=["*"],
                        allow_methods=["*"],
                        allow_headers=["*"],
                        allow_credentials=True,)
    @app.middleware("http")
    async def middleware(request,call_next):
        print("before")
        response= await call_next(request)
        print("after")
        return response


    allow_origins ->> which frontend is allowed
    allow_methods ->> which HTTP methods are allowed
    allow_headers ->> which headers are allowed
    allow_credentials ->> cookies/sessions support
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What is Middleware:
    Middleware is a function that runs before and after every API request
    It allows running common logic for all APIs without writing code in each route
    Middleware works like a gatekeeper for APIs
    It can be used to control,monitor, or log requests
    Middleware runs automatically once registered
    No need to call middleware inside path operations
    Middleware executes outside the route logic
    Typical uses:
        logging requests
        security checks
        performance monitoring
        Request validation at entry level
    Middleware is usually registered in main.py
    Multiple middlewares can be used and they executed in defined order
